name: Design of a Portfolio Management Office
description: The client wanted to develop an enterprise wide Project Management Office and asked Caravel to design the portfolio management structure and processes.

name: Closure of an Industrial Plant
description: Nationwide rail company KiwiRail chose to close an industrial plant that manufactured rolling stock and replacement parts.

name: Investment Logic Mapping (ILM)
description: A government agency used a series of ILM workshops to make significant changes to one of its core business areas, where their operating policies were not delivering good outcomes for their clients.

name: Implementation of a Financial Management System
description: In the wake of substantial organisational change, a major insurance company found that their financial management information system (FMIS) no longer met the organisation’s future needs.

name: Project Management Office for Major Business Change
description: Caravel helped a District Health Board to move its services into a new hospital.

name: Project Management Office for Law Enforcement
description: A law enforcement organisation appointed Caravel to run the Project Management Office and ensure that major programmes of work were initiated and completed correctly.

name: Change of Telecommunications Service Provider
description: A major banking institution wanted to ensure that it was receiving best value for money for its telecommunications expenditure.

name: Provision of Independent Quality Assurance
description: As preferred supplier to a major Government organisation, Caravel conducts Independent Quality Assurance and Post Implementation Reviews for major, high profile projects involving significant organisational, process and technology changes.

name: Program Management Review
description: Caravel’s client had recently identified a shortcoming in their project delivery capability and needed guidance on how to fix the problem.

name: Business Process Innovation
description: Caravel carried out a feasibility study to determine whether the national Maritime Safety Radio Service could be provided more effectively and economically, given changes in technology, shipping and international maritime laws.
